#  Level 1 Help Desk Home Lab (Active Directory)

## Overview
For this project I built out a Windows Active Directory lab to simulate a small company environment and practice real help desk tasks.

The main goal was to get hands-on with things like:
- Password resets and account unlocks  
- User creation and permissions  
- DNS and domain issues  
- Group Policy (GPO)  
- Shared drives and access control  

Instead of just setting it up, I ran through real ticket scenarios and documented how I fixed each one.

---

## Lab Setup
- Domain Controller: Windows Server 2022 (DC01)  
- Domain: mattlab.local  
- Clients: CL01 + CL02  
- Network: Internal lab network (routed through pfSense)

### What I set up:
- Created OUs to organize users and computers  
- Created users + security groups  
- Set DNS on clients to point to the domain controller  
- Built a shared drive with proper permissions  

---

## Ticket Scenarios

### Ticket 1 — Password Reset
**Issue:** User couldn’t log in (forgot password)

**What I did:**
- Found the user in Active Directory  
- Reset the password  
- Forced password change at login  

**Result:** User logged in and updated password successfully  

---

### Ticket 2 — Account Lockout
**Issue:** User locked out after too many failed attempts  

**What I did:**
- Checked account status in AD  
- Unlocked the account  
- Reset password just in case  

**Root cause:** Account lockout policy triggered  

**Result:** User was able to log in again  

---

### Ticket 3 — New User Onboarding
**Issue:** New employee needed an account + access  

**What I did:**
- Created user in Active Directory  
- Added them to SalesUsers + SharedDrive_RO  
- Set temp password  

**Result:** User logged in and accessed shared drive  

---

### Ticket 4 — User Deactivation
**Issue:** Employee left the company  

**What I did:**
- Disabled the account  
- Moved it to Disabled Users OU  
- Removed all group memberships  

**Result:** Account fully secured and no longer usable  

---

### Ticket 5 — Shared Drive Access Denied
**Issue:** User couldn’t access shared drive  

**What I did:**
- Reproduced the issue on client machine  
- Checked group membership  
- Added user to correct shared drive group  
- Ran gpupdate  

**Root cause:** User wasn’t in the correct group  

**Result:** Access restored  

---

### Ticket 6 — Domain Join Failure (aka it’s always DNS)
**Issue:** Client couldn’t join domain  

**What I did:**
- Checked IP config  
- Found DNS was set to 8.8.8.8  
- Tested with nslookup (failed)  
- Changed DNS to domain controller  

**Root cause:** Wrong DNS server  

**Result:** Domain join worked after fix  

---

### Ticket 7 — Login Failure After Password Change
**Issue:** User couldn’t log in after changing password  

**What I did:**
- Verified account wasn’t locked or disabled  
- Reset password  
- Checked for user-side issues (caps lock, username format)  
- Verified connection to domain controller  

**Root cause:** Most likely user input error  

**Result:** User logged in successfully  

---

### Ticket 8 — GPO Not Applying (this one sucked)
**Issue:** Policy wasn’t applying to user  

**What I did:**
- Ran gpupdate /force  
- Checked gpresult /r  
- Verified OU placement  
- Found GPO wasn’t linked correctly  

**Root cause:** User in wrong OU / GPO not linked  

**Result:** Policy applied after fixing OU/link  

---

### Ticket 9 — Network Drive Mapping
**Issue:** Users needed shared drive automatically  

**What I did:**
- Verified manual access first  
- Created GPO for drive mapping  
- Linked it to Users OU  

**Result:** Drive mapped automatically on login  

---

### Ticket 10 — Software Deployment from Network Share
**Issue:** User needed access to internal installer  

**What I did:**
- Placed installer in shared folder  
- Verified permissions  
- Accessed and ran from client machine  

**Result:** User was able to run installer  

